{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "We now present an in-depth legal and technical critique of the DSA along with psychological, behavioral and ethical perspectives to enable a holistic, evidence-based assessment.foot_1 Legal and technical critiqueAs the analysis of the ECD and 2018's CPD revealed, persistent gaps remain regarding inconsistent definitional precision, uneven transparency and accountability mechanisms, constrained oversight across platforms, and limited harmonization in responsibilities and redress options [102,170].",
    "The subsequent legal and technical critique examines precisely how such issues manifest as lingering ambiguities, discretionary authority and procedural weaknesses within the DSA framework itself.Definitional Ambiguities Open questions around what constitutes a \"systemic risk\" under the DSA (Code: RA) stand [169].",
    "Views diverge on \"whether a systemic risk is one that has an impact on a system and, if so, which system(s), or if it is a risk that is caused or exacerbated by a system\" [82].",
    "This ambiguity around the core notion of systemic risk creates implementation challenges for platforms undertaking assessments, especially given the availability of public DSA readiness checklists [173].",
    "Alongside that, the definition of \"harmful\" content tackled through notice-and-takedown procedures (Code: NTD) in Articles 14-15 lacks binding legal force and grants excessive discretion to platforms over concepts like intent, truth and harm without adequate precision (Article 26) [109]."
  ],
